text:
This looks like the kind of situation where the creators started out with just a basic mobile camera and just started saying: "It would be cool if it had this, and this, and this, feature.." and then they just really, actually, added all those features.
It's rare that you see a product as well designed as this. Usually it's the consumer who says "It would be cool if it had.." months later, and then they just forget about it because they know it's never going to happen.

text:
Since I didn't hear it or see it: ND stands for "neutral density" filters.  The idea being that you want a filter that is "grey" in that it blocks the same amount of all colors of light.  Think of like a theater "red" filter.  That blocks everything that isn't red, so you get red light.  (Imagine other colors here).  
This is designed so that a super super bright light (like the sun, or the moon maybe?) is 1000 or 10000 or 1000000 times fainter than it usually would be, so then your camera can take a picture and see sunspots, or moon craters, or like, Jenna on a beach, under the noon-day Hawaii sun.
